<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<?import javafx.scene.layout.*?>
<?import javafx.scene.control.*?>
<?import javafx.geometry.Insets?>

<BorderPane xmlns:fx="http://javafx.com/fxml"
            fx:controller="game.of.life.on.gpu.ui.TheoryController"
            stylesheets="@../css/dark-theme.css"
            style="-fx-background-color: #0A0F19;">

    <!-- Top: Back button -->
    <top>
        <HBox alignment="CENTER_LEFT" style="-fx-padding: 12 16;">
            <Button text="← BACK" styleClass="back-button" onAction="#goBack"/>
        </HBox>
    </top>

    <!-- Center: Scrollable theory content -->
    <center>
        <ScrollPane fitToWidth="true" hbarPolicy="NEVER"
                    style="-fx-background: transparent; -fx-background-color: transparent;">
            <VBox spacing="24" alignment="TOP_CENTER" maxWidth="800">
                <padding><Insets top="20" right="40" bottom="60" left="40"/></padding>

                <!-- Hero Title -->
                <Label text="The Theory of Cellular Automata"
                       style="-fx-text-fill: #00FFE0; -fx-font-size: 32px; -fx-font-weight: bold;
                              -fx-effect: dropshadow(gaussian, #00FFE040, 16, 0.3, 0, 0);"/>
                <Label text="A deep dive into one of mathematics' most elegant discoveries"
                       style="-fx-text-fill: rgba(255,255,255,0.45); -fx-font-size: 12px;"/>

                <!-- Section I: Origins -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="I. ORIGINS &amp; HISTORY" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>
                    <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                           text="In 1970, British mathematician John Horton Conway, a professor at Cambridge University, invented the Game of Life while exploring a question first posed by the legendary John von Neumann in the 1940s: Is it possible to create a simple machine that can build copies of itself?&#10;&#10;Von Neumann's original self-replicating automaton required 29 possible cell states and incredibly complex rules. Conway's genius was in distilling the concept down to just TWO states (alive or dead) and FOUR rules, while preserving the profound computational power that made von Neumann's work so groundbreaking.&#10;&#10;The game was first brought to the world's attention through Martin Gardner's Mathematical Games column in Scientific American (October 1970), and it immediately captured the imagination of mathematicians, computer scientists, and hobbyists worldwide."/>
                </VBox>

                <!-- Section II: The Four Rules -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="II. THE FOUR RULES OF SURVIVAL" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>

                    <HBox spacing="12">
                        <VBox spacing="6" HBox.hgrow="ALWAYS"
                              style="-fx-background-color: rgba(231,76,60,0.06); -fx-border-color: rgba(231,76,60,0.2);
                                     -fx-border-radius: 8; -fx-background-radius: 8; -fx-padding: 12;">
                            <Label text="① UNDERPOPULATION" style="-fx-text-fill: #E74C3C; -fx-font-size: 12px; -fx-font-weight: bold;"/>
                            <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                                   text="A live cell with fewer than 2 live neighbors dies of loneliness."/>
                        </VBox>
                        <VBox spacing="6" HBox.hgrow="ALWAYS"
                              style="-fx-background-color: rgba(46,213,115,0.06); -fx-border-color: rgba(46,213,115,0.2);
                                     -fx-border-radius: 8; -fx-background-radius: 8; -fx-padding: 12;">
                            <Label text="② SURVIVAL" style="-fx-text-fill: #2ED573; -fx-font-size: 12px; -fx-font-weight: bold;"/>
                            <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                                   text="A live cell with 2 or 3 live neighbors continues to thrive."/>
                        </VBox>
                    </HBox>
                    <HBox spacing="12">
                        <VBox spacing="6" HBox.hgrow="ALWAYS"
                              style="-fx-background-color: rgba(255,159,67,0.06); -fx-border-color: rgba(255,159,67,0.2);
                                     -fx-border-radius: 8; -fx-background-radius: 8; -fx-padding: 12;">
                            <Label text="③ OVERPOPULATION" style="-fx-text-fill: #FF9F43; -fx-font-size: 12px; -fx-font-weight: bold;"/>
                            <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                                   text="A live cell with more than 3 live neighbors dies of overcrowding."/>
                        </VBox>
                        <VBox spacing="6" HBox.hgrow="ALWAYS"
                              style="-fx-background-color: rgba(0,255,224,0.06); -fx-border-color: rgba(0,255,224,0.2);
                                     -fx-border-radius: 8; -fx-background-radius: 8; -fx-padding: 12;">
                            <Label text="④ REPRODUCTION" style="-fx-text-fill: #00FFE0; -fx-font-size: 12px; -fx-font-weight: bold;"/>
                            <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                                   text="A dead cell with exactly 3 live neighbors springs to life."/>
                        </VBox>
                    </HBox>
                </VBox>

                <!-- Section III: Why It Matters -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="III. WHY THE GAME OF LIFE MATTERS" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>
                    <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                           text="TURING COMPLETENESS&#10;&#10;The Game of Life is Turing Complete. This is a staggering fact: a grid of black and white squares with four trivial rules has the same raw computational power as any modern computer. Logic gates (AND, OR, NOT), memory registers, and even entire CPUs have been constructed entirely within the Game of Life.&#10;&#10;In 2000, Paul Rendell built a working Turing machine inside the game. In 2010, a complete programmable computer was constructed. This means, in theory, you could run Windows, play video games, or simulate another Game of Life — all inside a Game of Life.&#10;&#10;THE UNDECIDABILITY PROBLEM&#10;&#10;Because it is Turing Complete, the fate of any starting pattern is formally 'undecidable.' There is no shortcut algorithm that can predict whether a given pattern will eventually die out, stabilize, or grow forever, without actually simulating every single step. This connects directly to Alan Turing's Halting Problem (1936)."/>
                </VBox>

                <!-- Section IV: Emergence -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="IV. EMERGENCE &amp; COMPLEXITY SCIENCE" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>
                    <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                           text="The Game of Life is the most famous demonstration of EMERGENCE: complex, unpredictable behavior arising from extremely simple rules. No single cell 'knows' anything about the global pattern, yet together they produce structures that move, replicate, compute, and even evolve.&#10;&#10;This principle underpins modern complexity science and has profound implications:&#10;&#10;• BIOLOGY: How do trillions of simple cells create consciousness?&#10;• PHYSICS: How do elementary particles give rise to galaxies?&#10;• ECONOMICS: How do billions of individual decisions create market crashes?&#10;• NEUROSCIENCE: How do networks of neurons produce thought?&#10;&#10;Stephen Wolfram's 'A New Kind of Science' (2002) argues that simple rules like Conway's may be the fundamental mechanism underlying all of nature's complexity."/>
                </VBox>

                <!-- Section V: Famous Patterns -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="V. FAMOUS PATTERNS &amp; AUTOMATA" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>
                    <HBox spacing="12">
                        <VBox spacing="4" HBox.hgrow="ALWAYS"
                              style="-fx-background-color: rgba(241,196,15,0.05); -fx-border-color: rgba(241,196,15,0.15);
                                     -fx-border-radius: 8; -fx-background-radius: 8; -fx-padding: 12;">
                            <Label text="STILL LIFES" style="-fx-text-fill: #F1C40F; -fx-font-size: 12px; -fx-font-weight: bold;"/>
                            <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text" text="Stable — never change.&#10;Block, Beehive, Loaf, Boat."/>
                        </VBox>
                        <VBox spacing="4" HBox.hgrow="ALWAYS"
                              style="-fx-background-color: rgba(46,213,115,0.05); -fx-border-color: rgba(46,213,115,0.15);
                                     -fx-border-radius: 8; -fx-background-radius: 8; -fx-padding: 12;">
                            <Label text="OSCILLATORS" style="-fx-text-fill: #2ED573; -fx-font-size: 12px; -fx-font-weight: bold;"/>
                            <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text" text="Flip between states.&#10;Blinker (p2), Pulsar (p3),&#10;Pentadecathlon (p15)."/>
                        </VBox>
                        <VBox spacing="4" HBox.hgrow="ALWAYS"
                              style="-fx-background-color: rgba(0,212,255,0.05); -fx-border-color: rgba(0,212,255,0.15);
                                     -fx-border-radius: 8; -fx-background-radius: 8; -fx-padding: 12;">
                            <Label text="SPACESHIPS" style="-fx-text-fill: #00D4FF; -fx-font-size: 12px; -fx-font-weight: bold;"/>
                            <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text" text="Move across the grid.&#10;Glider, LWSS, MWSS, HWSS.&#10;Glider = the icon of the game."/>
                        </VBox>
                    </HBox>
                    <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                           text="ADVANCED PATTERNS&#10;&#10;• METHUSELAHS: Tiny patterns that take thousands of generations to stabilize. The R-pentomino (just 5 cells) takes 1,103 generations and produces 6 gliders.&#10;&#10;• GUNS: Infinite engines that periodically shoot spaceships. Bill Gosper's Glider Gun (1970) was the first, proving that unbounded growth is possible — winning a $50 prize from Conway himself.&#10;&#10;• PUFFERS &amp; RAKES: Moving objects that leave debris trails or shoot gliders behind them.&#10;&#10;• GARDEN OF EDEN: Patterns that cannot arise from any predecessor — they can only exist as initial conditions, never as evolved states."/>
                </VBox>

                <!-- Section VI: Real-World Applications -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="VI. REAL-WORLD APPLICATIONS" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>
                    <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                           text="The Game of Life is far more than a mathematical curiosity:&#10;&#10;• CRYPTOGRAPHY: Cellular automata (Rule 30) power the random number generator in Mathematica and have been used in stream cipher design.&#10;&#10;• BIOLOGY: CA models simulate tumor growth, neural networks, epidemic spread, and ecological population dynamics.&#10;&#10;• PHYSICS: Lattice gas automata simulate fluid dynamics. CAs model crystal growth, forest fires, and seismic wave propagation.&#10;&#10;• COMPUTER SCIENCE: CAs are used in parallel computing research, VLSI circuit testing, image processing, and procedural content generation in video games.&#10;&#10;• PHILOSOPHY: The Game of Life fuels debates about determinism, free will, and whether our universe itself might be a cellular automaton (Digital Physics)."/>
                </VBox>

                <!-- Section VII: GPU Acceleration -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="VII. GPU ACCELERATION &amp; THIS PROJECT" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>
                    <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                           text="This application demonstrates how the Game of Life maps perfectly onto GPU hardware.&#10;&#10;Each pixel on the GPU processes one cell independently and simultaneously through a GLSL fragment shader. The 'conway.glsl' shader samples 8 texture neighbors, counts alive cells, and outputs the next state — all in parallel across thousands of GPU cores.&#10;&#10;The ping-pong buffer technique alternates between two framebuffers: one is read as a texture (current generation), the other is written to (next generation). After each iteration, they swap. This allows the GPU to compute 100,000+ generations in seconds, a task that would take minutes on the CPU.&#10;&#10;This is the same parallel computing paradigm used in machine learning, physics simulation, ray tracing, and scientific computing."/>
                </VBox>

                <!-- Section VIII: Beyond Conway -->
                <VBox styleClass="glass-card" spacing="10">
                    <Label text="VIII. BEYOND CONWAY'S RULES" styleClass="section-title"/>
                    <Separator style="-fx-border-color: transparent transparent rgba(0,255,224,0.15) transparent;"/>
                    <Label wrapText="true" styleClass="body-text"
                           text="Version 7.0 of this project introduces MULTIPLE RULE SETS, proving that Conway's rules are just one point in an infinite space of cellular automata:&#10;&#10;• HIGHLIFE (B36/S23): Identical to Conway except birth also occurs at 6 neighbors. This single change creates a 'replicator' — a pattern that copies itself!&#10;&#10;• DAY &amp; NIGHT (B3678/S34678): A symmetric rule where dead and alive cells are interchangeable. Produces beautiful, organic, expanding patterns.&#10;&#10;• SEEDS (B2/S): Every cell dies after exactly one generation. Creates explosive, fractal-like growth patterns — pure ephemeral beauty.&#10;&#10;• DIAMOEBA (B35678/S5678): Grows diamond-shaped amoeba-like blobs that merge and split unpredictably. Demonstrates how tiny rule changes create alien worlds.&#10;&#10;V7.0 also adds a HEATMAP mode that colors cells by age, revealing which structures are ancient (white-hot) versus freshly born (cool blue)."/>
                </VBox>
            </VBox>
        </ScrollPane>
    </center>
</BorderPane>
